Note : If mass ' [latex]m[/latex] ' move by [latex]x[/latex], then block [latex]A[/latex] by [latex]2 x[/latex]. Data given : [latex]
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{m} & =10 \mathrm{Kg} \\
\mathrm{k} & =1.5 \mathrm{kN} / \mathrm{m}=1500 \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m} \\
\omega_{\mathrm{n}} & =?
\end{aligned}
[/latex] By D'Alembert's principle to mass [latex]m[/latex] [latex]
\begin{aligned}
m \ddot{x}+4 k x+2 k x & =0 \\
\ddot{x}+\left(\frac{6 k}{m}\right) x & =0
\end{aligned}
[/latex] [latex]
\begin{aligned}
\omega_{\mathrm{n}} & =\sqrt{\frac{6 \mathrm{k}}{\mathrm{m}}}=\sqrt{\frac{6 \times 1500}{10}} \\
& =30 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{sec} .
\end{aligned}
[/latex]

[latex]
V_{123}=\omega_{2}\left(I_{12} I_{23}\right)=\omega_{3}\left(I_{13} I_{23}\right)
[/latex] In [latex]\Delta \mathrm{I}_{12} \mathrm{PI}_{23}[/latex] [latex]
\begin{array}{rlrl}
\frac{\mathrm{I}_{12} \mathrm{I}_{23}}{\sin 60} & =\frac{\mathrm{I}_{12} \mathrm{P}}{\sin 75} \\
